<span id="v.iv.xxviii-p1"></span> <span class="c12"><span
id="v.iv.xxviii-p1.1"></span>Chapter XXVII.</span>

<span id="v.iv.xxviii-p2"></span><span class="c12"><span
id="v.iv.xxviii-p2.1"></span>Ursinus <span
id="fr_2617"></span>[2618](#fn_2617.md) </span> the monk wrote against
those who say that heretics should be rebaptized, teaching <span
id="fr_2618"></span>[2619](#fn_2618.md) that it is not legitimate nor
honouring God, that those should be rebaptized who have been baptized
either in the name of Christ alone or in the name of the Father and of
the Son and of the Holy Spirit, though the formula has been used in a
vitiated sense. He considers that after the simple confession of the
Holy Trinity and of Christ, the imposition of the hands of the catholic
priest is sufficient for salvation.

